  1. Get a frequency breakdown of the number of chicks, their average weight and the standard deviation of the weights in each of the diets at the start of the study. Store the resulting data frame in a variable named weight0 and print.
weight0 <- ChickWeight %>%
  filter(Time == 0) %>%
  summarize(num = n(), avg_weight = mean(weight), sd_weight = sd(weight))

weight0
##   num avg_weight sd_weight
## 1  50      41.06  1.132272

There are 50 chicks, their average weight is 41.06 gm and the standard deviation is 1.1322 gm

  1. Each chick should have twelve weight measurements. Use the dplyr package to identify how many measurements are there for each chick. Extract a subset of the data for all chicks with complete information, name the data set complete, and print the first 3 rows. (Hint: you might want to use mutate to introduce a helper variable consisting of the number of observations)
ChickWeight %>%
  group_by(Chick) %>%
  summarize(measurements = n()) -> meas

ChickWeight <- ChickWeight %>%
  inner_join(meas)
## Joining, by = "Chick"
complete <- ChickWeight %>%
  filter(measurements == 12)

head(complete, 3)
##   weight Time Chick Diet measurements
## 1     42    0     1    1           12
## 2     51    2     1    1           12
## 3     59    4     1    1           12
  1. In the complete data set introduce a new variable that measures the current weight difference compared to day 0. Name this variable weightgain and print the first 3 rows of the new data frame.
init_weights <- complete %>%
  filter(Time == 0) %>%
  group_by(Chick) %>%
  summarize(init_weights = min(weight))

complete <- complete %>%
  inner_join(init_weights)
## Joining, by = "Chick"
complete <- complete %>%
  mutate(weightgain = weight - init_weights)

head(complete, 3)
##   weight Time Chick Diet measurements init_weights weightgain
## 1     42    0     1    1           12           42          0
## 2     51    2     1    1           12           42          9
## 3     59    4     1    1           12           42         17
  1. Use {ggplot2} to create side-by-side boxplots of weightgain by Diet for day 21. Change the order of the categories in the Diet variable such that the boxplots are ordered by median weightgain, and the lower limit of the y axis should be 0. Describe the relationship in 2-3 sentences.
complete %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(Diet, weightgain, FUN = median), y = weightgain)) +
  geom_boxplot()

There seems to be some diets that are more effective in gaining weight than others. Diet 1 has the lowest median and IQR by quite a bit. Diets 3 & 4 have pretty close medians but Diet 4 has a more narrow IQR than Diet 3.

complete %>%
  filter(Time == 21) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Chick, y = weightgain, color = ifelse(Chick == 35 | Chick == 24, "red", "blue"))) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Colored blue is the highest fain and the lowest gain in weight, all others are colored red.

  1. For the chicks with the least and the most weight at time 0, plot their growth trajectories over time. 
minweight <- min(complete$init_weights)
maxweight <- max(complete$init_weights)

complete <- complete %>%
  mutate(extreme = ifelse(init_weights == minweight | init_weights == maxweight, 1, 0))

cw_extreme <- complete %>%
  filter(extreme == 1) %>%
  select(Time, Chick, weight)

cw_extreme %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Time, y = weight, group = Chick, color = Chick)) +
  geom_line()

  1. Add to the previous plot the average growth trajectory for all chicks (calculated as the mean weight for each chick at each time). How do the trajectories compare?
cw_average <- complete %>%
  group_by(Time) %>%
  summarize(Chick = "avg", weight = mean(weight))

cw_average %>%
  rbind(cw_extreme) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Time, y = weight, group = Chick, col = Chick)) +
  geom_line()

  1. What else do you find interesting in the dataset? Show your exploratory analysis.
